2515 /**
2516 * create account to be used by Router.
2517 *
2518 * `<host>` part of `<user>@<host>` will be %, unless user specified otherwise
2519 * using --account-host switch. Multiple --account-host switches are allowed.
2520 */
2521 1389 std::string ConfigGenerator::create_router_accounts(
2522 const std::map<std::string, std::string> &user_options,
2523 const std::set<std::string> &hostnames, const std::string &username,
2524 const std::string &password, bool password_change_ok) {
2525 /*
2526 Ideally, we create a single account for the specific host that the router is
2527 running on. But that has several problems in real world, including:
2528 - if you're configuring on localhost ref to metadata server, the router will
2529 think it's in localhost and thus it will need 2 accounts: user@localhost
2530 and user@public_ip... further, there could be more than 1 IP for the host,
2531 which (like lan IP, localhost, internet IP, VPN IP, IPv6 etc). We don't know
2532 which ones are needed, so either we need to automatically create all of
2533 those or have some very complicated and unreliable logic.
2534 - using hostname is not reliable, because not every place will have name
2535 resolution availble
2536 - using IP (even if we can detect it correctly) will not work if IP is not
2537 static
2538
2539 Summing up, '%' is the easy way to avoid these problems. But the decision
2540 ultimately belongs to the user.
2541 */
2542
2543 bool if_not_exists;
2544 {
2545 const std::string ac =

2642 /*static*/
2643 36 void ConfigGenerator::throw_account_exists(const MySQLSession::Error &e,
2644 const std::string &username) {
2645 // clang-format off
2646 // Extract a list of accounts that are reported to already exist.
2647 //
2648 // We do this by parsing error message we got back from the Server. In
2649 // English form, it looks like this:
2650 //

3091 * Get selected configuration options from the existing Router configuration

3093 **
3094 * ---
3095 * This function returns Router's id and SQL user for cluster `cluster_name`,
3096 * if it finds them in config file and they seem valid. If they're missing or
